1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1115":"1115","1059":"1059","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","Abt 1000":"circa 1000","Abt 1050":"circa 1050","Upper Normandy, France":"Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Arques-La-Bataille, Seine-Inferieure, Normandie":"Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Arques, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Arques-la-Bataille, Haute-Normandie, France":"Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1000–Abt 1050":"about 1000–about 1050","1010–1060":"1010–1060","1025–1086":"1025–1086","1030–1059":"1030–1059","1035–1086":"1035–1086","1040–1115":"1040–1115","1000–1050":"1000–1050","1000":"1000","1010":"1010","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1115":"1115","1059":"1059","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","Abt 1000":"about 1000","Abt 1050":"about 1050","Upper Normandy, France":"Upper Normandy, France","Arques-La-Bataille, Seine-Inferieure, Normandie":"Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","France":"France","Arques, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Arques-la-Bataille, Haute-Normandie, France":"Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Arques","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Mario, Luis, Fernando, Jorge, Armando, Ana, Joaquin, Julio, Marcos.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim, Paulo, Henrique, Lourenco, Seraphine, Vasco.","Catalan (<b>Marquès</b>); Spanish and southern French (<b>Marqués</b>): from Catalan <i>marquès</i>, Spanish and Occitan <i>marqués</i> ‘marquis’, words of French origin (see   Marquis  ), applied either as a nickname for someone who behaved like a marquis or as an occupational name for a servant in the household of a marquis.","Portuguese: patronymic from the personal name   Marcos  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marquis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Normand, Marcel, Fernand, Lucien, Rosaire, Andre, Armand, Camille, Cecile, Jacques, Francois.","French: from the title <i>marquis</i> ‘marquess’, applied as an ironic nickname to someone who behaved like a marquis or as a metonymic occupational name for a servant in the household of a marquis. The title, derived from an ancient Germanic word meaning ‘boundary’ (compare   March  ), originally referred to the governor of a border territory. Marquises did not form part of the original French feudal structure of nobility; the title was first adopted by the Counts of Toulouse because of their possessions in the border region beyond the Rhône. Compare   Markee   and   Markey  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>markis</i> ‘marquis, marquess, nobleman’ (Old French <i>marchis</i>); see also 1 above. The word is also found as a female personal name which may also be origin of the surname."]}]},{"name":"Godfrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French name <i>Godefroy</i>, which is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>god</i> ‘god’ (or <i>gōd</i> ‘good’) + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. This was adopted by the Normans, and brought to England by immigrants from the Low Countries and France. It was borne by a Norman saint (  <i>c.</i>1066–1115 ) who became bishop of Amiens. There has been considerable confusion with   Geoffrey ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Godfrey FitzGoscelin d'Arques was born about 1000, in Arques-la-Bataille, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Amelie Rouen. He died about 1050, at the age of 52."},"et":{"Abt 1000–Abt 1050":"umbes 1000–umbes 1050","1010–1060":"1010–1060","1025–1086":"1025–1086","1030–